title: New Extruder and Shredder concept - Using methods of innovative engineering (TRIZ)

description.text:
Based on the Bender24601-filament extruder, I have been tasked with the thesis project to simplify the existing system utilizing the engineering method TRIZ taught at TUM. There are some new concepts used in this model. I had direct access to the predecessor extruder from Bender24601, which allowed me to do a profound analysis of material used and its corresponding costs. The analysis has been done with the method TRIZ, which allows to evaluate each part to identify chances for improvement. Due to cost matters I have re-used the steppermotor and auger. The target was, to reduce machining parts, utilize printed parts as core components and furthermore increase the output. I was able to reach a significant cost reduction and increase of output up to 20cm per minute.
The parts required for the core extrude could be reduced. To allow a continuous production a filament control system has been added to remove the stress from the freshly extruded material. This allows a continuous production of a string without causing trouble you might have with longer extrusions.
The project has been accompanied with the Crusher module. I have also used a new concept compared to most of the crushers available. I will shortly upload the information and documentation (BOM and drawings)
Feel free to contact me if you have any questions.

description.text:
This print-in-place impossible screw has two interlocking pieces that twist freely but cannot come apart! A great example of an object that can be made with layer-by-layer 3D printing, but not with traditional manufacturing methods.

Check it out in this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jilYzgd4De0

The model is a remix of TheKre8Group's elegantly mind-bending Un-Manufacturable Part. We increased the clearance between the two parts, elongated the interior part with an extra twist, and added color to the inside twist for printing on full color 3D printers. We printed ours on the new XYZ da Vinci Color. The downloadable files also include models to use with dual-extrusion 3D printers and regular single-extrusion printers.

Modifying models to print in color has turned out be difficult with a capital D. For the full color model we used Meshmixer to "paint" the colors onto each vertex with the Sculpt tool. This sounds simple, except that the model started out with an overly sparse mesh on the top flat faces, which made the colors blend poorly and also act strangely when printed. After a lot of trial and error, including attempts at re-meshing with MakePrintable and MeshLab, we finally discovered that we could use "Make Solid" in Meshmixer to get a very nice overall homogenous new mesh around the object.

Here's a quick overview of the workflow we used to remix this model:

  • Thingiverse: Start with the Un-Manufacturable Part model from TheKre8Group
  • Meshmixer: Separate the two pieces into different files
  • Blender: Use displacement modifier to increase clearance on both pieces
  • Tinkercad: Cut out the center of the interior piece (so we can color just the top)
  • Meshmixer: Remesh using Make Solid, paint with Sculpt tool
  • XYZ: Slice so that interior piece prints with 50% infill, exterior with 20%
  • da Vinci Color printer: Print in one piece, with color added to each layer by the printer

title: Creality CR-10 use a Dial Indicator for Bed Leveling

description.text:
This dial indicator mount for the Creality CR-10 sits 2 mm in front of the extruder casing allowing the fan to stay on. The mount is made in 2 parts which are glued together. The dial indicator is fitted to the mount which is then pushed on the extruder casing. FreeCad files are included so you can modify the parts. Dial indicators can be bought for less then 10 Euro at Aliexpress. Some dial indicators need another backplate to mount them closer to the extruder.

To automate the bed-levelling process some gcode to just that is used. The gcode is best stored on the micro SD-card in the Creality. It can then be executed via the "Print from SD card" menu. ReptierHost doesnot handle the gcode well but the old Pronterface did.

During the leveling process the Creality will beep and display text messages when it moves. In each corner the dial indicator will touch the bed and you then have a 15 seconds time frame to level the bed. To verify all went well the dial indicator is lifted and will touch the bed again (10 seconds time frame). The gcode is available as a 1 and 2 pass version. During 1 pass all 4 corners are visited in a diagonal pattern. You can modify the gcode with a text-editor.

The video is here : https://youtu.be/8YACwSJbhvE

This is a combination / remix of bed levelling things of: CallJoe https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2412647 ; Caster https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2469518 ;
bebryan https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2499840 ; urnzwy https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2511825 ; and the backplate of muddtt https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:167459 .
The Gcode is derived from myfordboy's gcode at http://myfordboy.blogspot.nl/p/creality-cr-10.html .

By installing this minimalist case, it allows the Arduino to be placed onto a flat conductive surface without shorting it out.   
The bumper press fits onto the Arduino Uno and Leonardo. Recessed grooves located under where the Arduino pins sit allow the back of the board to sit flat in the bumper.   
Update: Arduino Bumper 0006 has mounting holes.

On an Ultimaker, this print took around 30mins when printed with PrintRun. I used Slic3r to generate Gcode with the following settings:
  • 0.1mm thickness layers
  • 6 solid layers on top and bottom
  • 0% density (hollow)
  • 2 perimeters/walls
  • 0.4mm nozzle
    • When printed at these settings, the walls of the bumper are two solidly fused perimeters. Varying results may occur with different size nozzles. Please let me know if there are problems. Note: The Arduino Leonardo might have a tighter fit because they do not have a clean cut on the top and bottom edges. I believe mine was scored and separated from a larger sheet when it was manufactured. Autodesk Inventor file included.

description.text:
Feiyue FY03 MG995 Servo Mod

This is a vertical adapter for the Feiyue FY03 to fit a TowerPro mg995 or other servos the same size.

You need to mark out and drill/melt 3 new holes in the base of the car to fit this new mount for your steering servo.

I used various pc screws, the screw & brass ring that come with the mg995 and 1 single washer.

Freecad saves included.

Things to note;
You might need to scale or trim the steering arm hole that fits onto the ball joint of the original steering of the car. Try to keep this tight to prevent speed wobbles whilst driving.

This is a simple blower fan adapter for the Intel Xeon Phi coprocessor. With this you can adapt a blower fan to the Phi to make a passively cooled coprocessor become actively cooled. This is ideal for use in systems that do not otherwise have enough cooling capacity for passively cooled devices such as Nvidia Tesla P100 or V100 GPUs.
This adapter was designed specifically to adapt the Xeon Phi 5110P to the Sunon PMB1212PLB1-A blower fan.
Two versions of this model are uploaded; the first is a straight adapter which keeps the blower in line with the Phi while the second is a curved adapter which puts the blower along side the Phi. You would use the first if you have the space in your server/case to fit length-wise and the second if you have the room to fit width-wise.
Note: due to the blower fans high CFM and high wattage draw, you'll need to power it directly from a standard molex connector - not from a motherboard.

Update 11.30.17 - a user mention the pins don't line up correctly when snapping cover over insert. Added R2Pi2 - Insert R2. This insert is undersized .030 to help with that issue. Looks to work really well to open up more tolerance. I am removing the original Insert R1 to keep the files simple.

The laser power should also be set to 0. Tutorials on how to insert picture and text and how to convert them to paths can be found online by various people.

Used the Radio Control Flying Bird from amazon.com ($30)
Broke it apart and rebuilt it using a 3d printer and tissue paper with a deltang ultra micro 2.4 Ghz receiver. BTW, there is a light in the birds head... I pull it out and re glue the bird head by sandwiching a glue soaked piece of tissue paper between the 2 foam pieces. Otherwise the glue i use eats away at the foam. Video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lDUt2XtjvdM

description.text:
I got sick of those 2 loud fans inside the original case and decided to draw new case with single 120x15mm slim fan. I don´t know if the older CR-10 board fits, new with Mega2560 sure does. Inside the case is also a mount for RaspberryPi 3 to run octopi, it sits on high poles to fit those printer cables under RaspberryPi´s usb and network cables.

NECESSARY MODS:

  1. With this case you have to mount PSU external, that one you have to figure out by yourself. Search PSU case, I found this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1745609

  2. Also you should install some sort of rubber feet/addhesive tape etc, case is sliding all over my table without some friction between them.

  3. On the backside of 12864 board is a speaker, you have to desolder it and solder it to the front side. This makes the display case slimmer.

  4. You need slim 120mm fan to top part, I used Silverstone FW121: http://www.silverstonetek.com/product.php?pid=500
    I shortened the cable to 5cm and soldered Noctua Low Noise Adapter wire to positive. It is still spinning too fast, I will try some resistors to get it to lower rpm. Use FAN1-3 connectors on Melzi to power it, there are 2 extras now that were powering those original noisy case fans.

  5. You will also might need a special USB-cable from RaspberryPi to S-Melzi. I made one myself, but ones on the market might just as well work.

Updates

04.11.2017
Added pictures of working proto, I´m redesigning it atm. Adding 10mm to height and widening 20mm, then there will be enough room to use normal usb cord between Melzi and Raspberry. You can see the custom made one in place now.

I´m also modding those vents, they don´t print very good now. Making them more horizontal than vertical.

New print will be ready by tomorrow, I´ll upload new models then.

06.11.2017
New top part printing now, I added mount for the display directly to part. Display case printing tomorrow.

07.11.2017
12864 case finished, assembled case added.

08.11.2017
I modified top part with more robust display mount, it was too weak and tended to bend little when button was used. It also prints better now. Will add models and photos as I get print out.

13.11.2017
I smoothed some corners and decided that it is good enough for me.

24.12.2017
Added few pictures of the new design. I'm no longer using this case, I'm designing new case for Duet Wifi. It will mount vertical to CR-10S frame.

title: Blade of the Faith (Dragon Age: Inquisition Sword)

description.text:
This sword is based on the first sword wielded by Cassandra Pentaghast in Dragon Age: Inquisition, emblazoned the Inquisiton's symbol. The finished sword, full size, is 90 cm long (which is a good length to hang from a belt if you're about my height, 170cm) but can be made longer or shorter by printing a different number of blade sections.

The blade is intentionally a little overly thick due to Dutch law about walking around in public with fake weapons that could be at all mistaken for real. You're welcome to modify it and thin it to your liking (as long as you're not planning on being in public with it in the Netherlands).

Print one copy of each section, except 4 - you'll need to print 3 of these. The only section that will need support is the crosspiece (3). The sections are glued together with superglue, which works pretty well with flat sections in PLA. The center has a cutout into which I glued a dowel, to help with stability. To finish, sand and prime until you cry, and then sand and prime some more, and when you've finally lost your will to live, paint it and wrap the handle in leather. Because of the sanding required, there's some parts that come to a slightly sharper edge along the vertical symmetry than intended, but I didn't bother correcting as you'd be sanding it anyway.

description.text:
A remix of an iPhone dock and an Apple Watch dock I liked and wanted to combine.
For me it was important to have a simple and stable design which prints easily with as little post processing (no supports etc.) required as possible and which is easy to print.

The iPhone dock is designed to work with common iPhone covers so you don't have to free it from the case whenever you place it on the dock to charge. (tested with iPhone 6, 6s, 8. Plus versions might work as well even though they might extend the width of the dock)

You might want to put 4 rubber buffers below so the dock will not move when putting your iPhone on it.

There are two versions of the dock.
One that is plain without a logo.
Another one on which you can add a logo (plain preset so you can put on a logo or letters of your choice). For this you need to print the logo + 2x the connector (print the connectors very slow and with 100% infill as you may need to file these to fit depending on how accurate your printer is.

Notes:

Important tip to make sure the dock will work for sure:
If your filament tends to shrink (I experienced different behaviours of different brands) you might want to go with 101% scaling to avoid the cables not to fit or fit too tight. => A loose fit you can fix with a drop of glue, a too small print is a waste of filament.

Some general tips for the look of the print:
-You may print with a brim if your prints tend to warp or come off the heatbed during print.
-Depending on your printer/filament you might want to print with a thicker wall (I print with 1mm) to avoid exposing the infill. - same goes to top surface, be sure the surfaces look smooth on your test cube or whatever you use.
Maybe also reduce the jerk (I put mine to 10-12) to reduce ghosting as this will just not look good due the big surface to the front.

title: Heavy Duty Y Axis for Wilson II

description.text:
This is a rework of the Y axis for the Wilson 2 to make it significantly stronger. Due to the plastic ends used on the Wilson 2, any belt tension causes the motor mount to bow downward, which could cause backlash and eventual part failure. So I encorporated matsekberg's awesome design he did for the Anet A8, to use threaded rods for the belt tensioner to remove all tension from the plastic. I have also redesigned the Y-Idler and Y-Motor mounts to be significantly stronger.

You'll need two ~450mm long M6 threaded rods. You should be able to buy 1M from Fastenal for like $5. You'll also need 4 M6 nuts. Although if you have an M6 tap, I've included printable nuts. You'll need the tap to clean the threads though. I've designed the parts to use M4 screws to mount to the aluminum extrusion parts. The tensioner uses an M3 x 16mm and an M3 nut. You can use a 16T idler or a pair of F693ZZ bearings for the tensioner. The motor mount screws are M3 x 14mm.

description.text:
I love my Hictop printer but the standard aluminium bed is useless, It's not flat whether it's hot or cold. The inductive sensor won't work on glass and getting a longer range one to detect the bed through the glass simply means the head will level against the bed not the glass.
This mount enables a standard 18mm capacitive sensor to be used in place of the inductive one.
You will need to drill out the mounting holes in the bearing carrier to 3.5mm then thread the holes in the bearing block with an M4 tap. Mount the bracket using M4 x 8mm cap head bolts
The sensor is then a simple push fit through mount. I have the lower threads on the sensor just inside the lower hoop so when the print nozzle is touching the build plate the sensor is a few mm from the bed.

Hi friends,

I don't know about you, but I'm unable to evaluate the good size of the small screws I use for my Geetech I3 Pro B. So I decided to make a gadget for that.
There are 2 pieces. One with the scale and the other with holes where screws have to be inserted. Then you slide the second until the screw stops the slider. And you read the size just under.
The slider has 3 holes: 2.5, 3 and 4. You can measure screws from 6mm to 30mm every 2mm. I added too 25mm. It is very easy to use.
I only painted the digits with a marker but you can print cleanly by inserting the M600 code for changing filament juste before the digits.

As I don't know how to post animated gifs on TG, here is a link to see how that works :
https://image.noelshack.com/fichiers/2017/44/5/1509730896-video.gif

I hope you will like it and that it will be useful for you. Feel free to leave a Like or comment. It's always nice and it does not cost much.

At first, please pay attention, the FC have to be installed in the right way! Tail of the Frame has small notch for the powercable, so you can see what is front and back. If you don't do it in the right way the FC board is not right in the middle of the Frame!

This is a self designed true X frame for the Graupner Alpha 110 FPV Copter. You can take all electronics out of the Alpha and put it into my Frame. It's 100mm diagonal from motor to motor. It is flying better then the original Graupner Frame, very agile and you can fly more agressive maneuvers :) With some tuning motors it will be very exciting! You can choose from 3 Frames. The different ist the thickness. There are 3mm, 2.5mm and 2mm. Also you can choose from 2 Topplates. There are 1.5mm and 1mm. It's your choice between weight and stability ;) I made it in the lightest version 2mm Frame and 1mm Topplate. In this configuration the weight is 44g without lipo. The lipo tkes place on the bottom. There ist also a tool to press in the motors, with this simple tool it is much easier ;) you can use it for all 8520 Motors.

You also need to build it:
4x M3x10 plastic screw
4x 1,9x3x5 o-ring (softmount FC)
4x M3 in/out x 10 stand off
8x M3 plastic nut
some 2 or 3mm thick adhasive foam
a little piece of double sided adhasive foam tape (3M) to mount the cam and a little bit foam as protection for the cam.
cable tie, or rubber band.
And if you want light in the front and back 2x 3mm LED
In the rear of the Topplate ist a holder for the 3mm LED
The motor press tool will help you press in the Motors!
Take a look at the pictures, they will help you to build the copter!

Achtung, das Flightcontroller Board muss richtig herum eingebaut werden, da die Löcher nicht symetrisch sind. Das Heck des Frames hat eine Kerbe. Wird der FC verkehrt herum eingebaut sitzt das Board nicht genau mittig.

Dies ist ein selbsdesignter true X Rahmen für den Graupner Alpha 110. Sämtliche Elektronik kann vom Original übernommen werden. FC, Kamera, VTX, Motoren. Der Rahmen hat eine diagonale von Motor zu Motor von 100mm. Er ist agiler und agressiver zu fliegen als das original. Nutzt man Tuning Motoren geht er noch besser los. Hier stehen 3 Frames zu Verfügung, die sich in ihrer Stärke unterscheiden. Zur Auswahl stehen 3mm. 2,5mm oder 2mm. Auch die Deckplatte gibt es in 2 Stärken 1,5mm und 1mm. So kann man wählen ob man mehr Stabilität möchte oder lieber ein paar Gramm leichter. In der leichtesten Version 2mm Rahmen und 1mm Deckplatte bei den unten angegebenen Druckparametern bringt er ohne Lipo 44g auf die Waage. Der Lipo wird an die Unterseite des Frames geschnallt. Außerdem befindet sich unter den Druck Dateien noch ein Motoreinpress Werkzeug. Damit ist es einfacher die Motoren in den Rahmen zu drücken. Es funktioniert für alle 8520 Bürstenmotoren.

Was man noch zum Bau benötigt:

4x M3x10 Plastik Schraube
4x 1,9x3x5 o-ring (softmount FC)
4x M3 in/außen Gewinde x 10mm Höhe
8x M3 Kunststoff Mutter
kleines Stück 2 oder 3mm dickes selbstklebendes Schaumgummi,
etwas geschäumtes doppelseitiges Klebeband z.B. von 3M um die Kamera anzubringen und dazu noch etwas Schaumstoff zum Schutz der Kamera.
Kabelbinder, oder Gummibänder zu Lipo Befestigung.

Wer Positionslichter vorn und hinten möchte, kann die vorderen Led Anschlüsse dafür nutzen, da diese dauernd leuchten. Für die Heckleuchte befindet sich ein Halter für eine 3mm LED in der Deckplatte, vorne reicht es sie einfach um 90 Grad angewinkelt einzubauen. Das Motoreinpresswerkzeug hilft beim vorsichtigen eindrücken der Motoren. Bitte auf die Kabel achten! Um die Motrren wieder zu entnehme vorsichtig eine Zange einsetzen und den Motor mit Gefühl oben an der Kante greifen.

Auf den Bildern wird jeder Bauschritt gezeigt.

description.text:
When I built my 3D printer I had little money and little resources in general. So I designed the overall of my printer thinking with cheap pieces but creative and and complex mechanism to compensate the lack of accurate sensors or strong metal pieces. This is the result of my solution for the z-probing, which is totally necessary for any delta printer.

I've have decided to write an article to establish some standards about how an informative scientific article should be written

Why this article. When I built my 3D printer I had little money and little resources in general. So I designed the overall of my printer thinking with cheap pieces but creative and and complex mechanism to compensate the lack of accurate sensors or strong metal pieces. This is the result of my solution for the z-probing, which is totally necessary for any delta printer. I've have decided to write an article to establish some standards about how an informative scientific article should be written even for the internet open build community.
The lesson is just the reading of an easy, basic, scientific style article to introduce newcomers to rigorous thinking.

The materials needed to use my implementation of this mechanism are an end-stop, two printed pieces, a calibrated rod (recommended) or a long M3 screw and an auxiliar screw to fix the rocker. But you may need to make your own design depending on your mechanical pieces and structural design.

description.text:
This is a set of spur gears for the Printrbot extruder. The original herringbone gears of the PB are not well suited for the application, IMO. The herringbones are sensitive to misalignment and give few benefits in return. The small spur gear is made wider then the large gear to allow for axial misalignment. The hubs are taken directly from the original Printrbot STLs. Gear ratio is the same as original. I have not yet printed or tested these yet but they seem to slice OK in Slic3r 0.8.4. Technical Data:
Diametral Pitch: 18
Pressure Angle: 20 deg
Small Gear (pinion): 13 teeth
Large Gear: 43 teeth
Addendum Modification Factor: 0.35
Solidworks files are 2011 version. Update: 05/07/12: -Deleted- See Update 3. Update 2: A PB plus user has printed and installed these with good results. Updated 3 (06/07/12): These gears should work for any of the Printrbot printed extruders. (PB original, LC and Plus) There may be some variation in some of the PB supplied parts out there but these are sized for the official released extruder. Note: Brook has mentioned a new laser cut extruder he is working on. Unknown what the gears will be on that. Update 4: 07/08/12: Added V2 of the large gear. Only change is the web section has been changed to full depth spokes. V1 parts will mesh fine with V2 - gear teeth are the same. My sample parts are printed at .4 layer height and my bot obviously needs some tuning ;) Updated 10/7/12: Added fixed versions of the V1 parts. Fixed by using Netfab's cloud service to get rid of the non-manifold conditions.
Print and assemble the same as you would for the original parts.

description.text:
I created this Lithophane lamp as an example for my local school Coder Dojo. If you would like to make one please follow the instructions per below.

Creating the Lithophanes (you'll need 4)

  • Find a picture that you want to use for your Lithophane. This image needs to have the correct dimensions to ensure that the Lithophane will fit. Please note, the dimensions of your image needs to be exactly 491(w)x658(h) pixels. If your image size is different, it may not fit in the frame. Most image software allows you to change the dimensions of your "canvas" to achieve the proper dimension. I have provided a blank image, open it up by navigating via the Thingiverse thumbnails. Right Click/ Save As to use it (it has the correct dimensions).

  • Go to the 3dp.rocks site. http://3dp.rocks/lithophane/ Go to the "settings" page and make the following changes:

  • Maximum Size (MM) - change to 75
  • Border (MM) - change to 1

  • Thickness (MM) - confirm it is 3

  • The other default settings should be fine. Next, go to the Images tab, upload your image. After that, go to the model tab, and press the "download" button.

  • Please note: the final dimensions of the Lithophane are 56(w)x75(h)mm, which includes a 1mm border around the entire lithophane.

  • Repeat step 2 above until you have all your images created. Feel free to also use the "blanklithophane.stl" if you want a lithophane that has nothing on it.

  • Use your slicer to print the Lithophanes. I recommend using 100% infill for anything with a picture on it. You can use 20% infill if you are just printing the blank.

Adjusting the Lithophane Frame

  • If you have changed the size of your Lithophane, you can modify the code to make it fit. I have included the source code. The code wasn't written to easily adjust (ideally, one could simply specify a height/width), but if you have decent programming skills you should be able to figure out how to adjust it. Please feel free to refactor/rewrite the code to make it more parameterized- incorporating some simple math / logic should do the trick. If you do that, post a remix!

  • You will need to use OpenSCAD to modify the code. It can be found at: http://www.openscad.org

The LED Light

  • For the LED light, I recommend using a 1 watt LED. These are similar to the ones I used, and they should fit in the case:
    https://www.amazon.com/Uxcell-a14073100ux0209-Emitter-Heatsink-3-0-3-6V/dp/B00S4U0XL4/

  • I recommend a USB cable with a small cord, at least 2-3ft in length. You can cut off one end and use the red/black wires. Plug the other end into a 5v power supply. An old cell phone charger will work fine, as long as it can put out at least 1 amp.
  • Here is an example of a power supply you could use: https://www.amazon.com/charger-FOBSUNLAND-Universal-Adapter-S6-Note/dp/B073Q1N8FL
  • Depending on the LED you use, you're going to need to solder a resistor in line on the positive wire before connecting to the LED. Verify the resistor you need using http://www.ledcalc.com If you are using the recommendations per above, you will need a 5.6 ohm 1 watt resistor. You can buy it here: https://www.mouser.com/ProductDetail/Ohmite/OX56GKE/?qs=sGAEpiMZZMvmQ%252bOLa8n%2fM14fcBcO8UjqVyDNvST7Y3k%3d
  • Not feeling up to soldering? No problem. Just find a tea light and use that. The only downside is that you won't want to glue the lid on in final assembly.

Assembly

  • Plan on around 1 hour 30 minutes for printing each Lithophane. The frame is also around that time.

If using an LED

  • Place your LED in the frame, and glue the wire down so it is flush with the bottom of the frame.
  • Slide all 4 panes in. Find a helper to hold the frame and panes so it is "square". Then hot glue the top on.

If using a Tea Light

  • Hot glue the corners of the Lithophane together at the top. Otherwise things aren't going to stay together.
  • Set the lid on top. You may want to use some double sided tape, or very thin velcro to help keep it secured but still be able to easily remove it.

Other Information

  • I printed my frame with PETG and my panels with ABS and PETG, which is what I happened to have available. PLA should also work well. I recommend using a light filament for anything that you want to shine through.

  • Please note, the example Lithophane Image is trademarked. Please contact Northwood Local Schools before using.

description.text:
The Thankful Turkey

Thanksgiving (in the United States) is slowly becoming a forgotten holiday. The steady encroachment of Black Friday into Thursday evening has weakened this traditional family event. Maybe we should take a stand against this rampant commercialism and extend this beloved holiday by giving thanks throughout the whole month of November? By printing and using The Thankful Turkey you annotate a whole month's worth of thanks on this bird's tail feathers. These thoughtful penned reflections can then be archived for future family gatherings or read out loud while waiting in a Black Friday sales line.

Some Quick Notes

  • You will need some paint for decorating your model: black, brown, gold, orange, red, tan, white

  • Make sure the two short toes align with each other

  • Attach the head to the body slightly twisted either left or right for a more whimsical expression

  • Use the smallest model for holding name cards and establishing seating assignments for dinner; use the back of these place cards for playfully annotating the person's dinner eating habits (e.g., "pie monster" or "gravy slurper")

  • Fold a paper fan for the larger models and use this fan for recording everyone's thanks

  • Remember to record the date on your "feathered" thanks

NOTE: The Thankful Turkey is an adaptation of a commercial product, "Turkey on the Table."

Being who I am, I rarely take anything for granted. Thus most subjects and technical even other stuff gets a 2nd, 3rd or even more questioning to verify the correctness or truth there-of. Having now assembled two 3D printers from different sources I found that the "auto homing" location differs radically between the two. Just to make things really interesting I checked the positions of the nozzle and auto level sensor relative to the center of the build bed. In one case the auto level sensor was closer to the physical center of the bed whilst in the other case the nozzle was closer. mmmm interesting that? This prompted me to create a simple test object to test the "real" "Printing" center of each printer taking into account the fact that CURA 3.0.4 places an object dead center according to the machine definition. The results are quite interesting.

Just a note to indicate that some makers commented that knowing the exact center is or even approximate center is irrelevant I just forged ahead as, to my mind, it actually is important.

Anyways enjoy unraveling the photo`s :-)

description.text:
This is designed in order to facilitate the creation and hanging of mosaics.
It was specifically designed to fit the tiles from the 100hex project https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2477471

The Holder.stl file has a cutout in the back which is used to fit a nail and hang it on the wall.
All the other panels connect together, as such a whole mosaic can be hanged easily, without glue or tape and with minimal damage to the wall (just 2 nails).

There is a 0.2mm gap between the tile and the panel, it should be a friction fit.
However, if your printer is extremely well tuned you might find you need to scale the tile by a tiny amount to ensure it stays secure.
The gap between the grooves and the tabs is 0.4mm as I found 0.2mm was too tight for assembly.

IMPORTANT : There are 2 type of panels, the ones starting with Edge_* have the edge at the top, the ones starting with Corner_* have the corner at the top (check the pictures for a better understanding)

Leave a comment if you have any suggestions or questions.

Prusa Xi3

Tiles :

  • Around 10g each
  • Between 1h30 and 2h to print
  • Prusa White PLA

Panels :

  • Around 26g each
  • A bit over 3h to print
  • Prusa Black PLA

For the whole project (11 tiles) I used 410g of filament

Cleanup

Because of the overhang in the slots used to connect the panels you might need to do some cleanup of failed bridges.

Most of the tiles required cleanup for me but that was my printer's fault.

The first time

I started designing the holder because I wanted to find a way to hang the (amazing) tiles from the 100hex project. I started with the "dentrite" tile and I put it corner up (you'll see why this is important)

I made the holder by offsetting an hexagon and putting a hole in the back of the plate I had created. Everything was done in an afternoon on Fusion 360, I printed it, it worked :D

Then I started seeing how I could make other panels connect together and create a mosaic that was easy to hang. So I looked for the best shape to connect my panels and found one that worked pretty well. I set on designing panels, trying to see which sides needed to be holes and which ones needed to be arms so that I could create any shape of mosaic.

Having done that I made all the different panels using my arm shape, an offset and playing with circular patterns to get all the different combinations.

And there I had it, all the panels, corner up

The second time

Having made all my panels I got back to the 100hex thingiverse page and found out that most of the tiles were edge up, rendering my work pretty limited.

So I sailed on a new journey, adapting my corner up panels into edge up panels. I can seem easy but I was pretty tedious, thinking about it now I should have started from scratch.

But I made it, and that's why there is both edge up and corner up panels.

Printed with 100% infill so no one will break it easily again.
The rotating interface between the selfie stick and the mobile phone clamp was broken. I've made the same piece in order to repair the selfie stick of my daughter.
